            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the Ohio local income tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                Ohio is unusual in that many cities, villages, and school
                districts levy their own income taxes in addition to state
                income tax. This calculator helps you estimate:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Municipal income tax (city or village where you live and/or
                  work)
                </li>
                <li>School district income tax (if your district has one)</li>
                <li>Total local income tax per pay period and per year</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Formulas used</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>1. Period wages</strong></p>
                <p>
                  We treat the wages you enter as the taxable base for local tax
                  (most municipalities tax earned income such as wages).
                </p>

                <p class="mt-2"><strong>2. Municipal income tax</strong></p>
                <p>Without credit for tax paid to another city:</p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Municipal Tax} = \text{Wages} \times
                  \frac{\text{Municipal Rate}}{100} \]
                </p>

                <p>With credit for tax paid to a work city:</p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Home City Tax} = \max\Bigl( 0,\; \text{Wages} \times
                  \bigl( \frac{\text{Home Rate}}{100} - \frac{\text{Work Rate}
                  \times \text{Credit \%}}{100 \times 100} \bigr) \Bigr) \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  In this simplified model we show only the net home city
                  liability. Your employer may withhold work city tax
                  separately.
                </p>

                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>3. School district income tax</strong>
                </p>
                <p>
                  For both traditional and earned-income-only districts, we
                  approximate:
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{School District Tax} = \text{Wages} \times
                  \frac{\text{SD Rate}}{100} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  In reality, traditional SD tax is based on Ohio taxable income
                  from your state return, not just wages. Use this as a rough
                  estimate only.
                </p>

                <p class="mt-2"><strong>4. Annualization</strong></p>
                <p>
                  We annualize by multiplying period amounts by a factor based
                  on pay frequency:
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li>Annual: factor = 1</li>
                  <li>Monthly: factor = 12</li>
                  <li>Biweekly: factor = 26</li>
                  <li>Weekly: factor = 52</li>
                </ul>

                <p class="mt-2"><strong>5. Effective local tax rate</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Effective Rate} = \frac{\text{Total Annual Local
                  Tax}}{\text{Annual Wages}} \times 100\% \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>
                Step-by-step: using the Ohio municipal income tax calculator
              </h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Select your pay frequency.</strong> Choose annual,
                  monthly, biweekly, or weekly so the tool can annualize
                  correctly.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter your gross wages for that period.</strong> Use
                  the amount before any taxes or deductions.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Pick your Ohio city or village.</strong> Select a
                  sample city to prefill a rate, or leave it on “custom” and
                  type your exact municipal rate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong
                    >Optionally model a credit for tax paid to another
                    city.</strong
                  >
                  If you live in one city and work in another, turn on the
                  credit toggle and enter:
                  <ul>
                    <li>The work city rate</li>
                    <li>
                      The percentage credit your home city allows (often 100% up
                      to the home rate)
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Add school district income tax if applicable.</strong>
                  Choose a sample district or enter your own rate and whether it
                  is “earned income only” or “traditional.”
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Click “Calculate Ohio Local Tax.”</strong> Review the
                  breakdown for this pay period and the annualized totals.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Understanding Ohio municipal income tax</h2>
              <p>
                Key points about Ohio municipal income tax, based on guidance
                from the Ohio Department of Taxation and municipal tax agencies:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Who pays?</strong> Residents of a city typically pay
                  tax on all earned income, and nonresidents pay on income
                  earned within that city.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Flat rates.</strong> Most cities use a flat percentage
                  rate (for example, 1.5% or 2.5%) on earned income.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Withholding.</strong> Employers withhold municipal tax
                  if they have a physical presence in the city and you work
                  there.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Credits.</strong> Many cities grant a credit for tax
                  you already paid to another municipality, but the credit
                  percentage and cap vary widely.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Administration.</strong> Some cities administer their
                  own tax; others use regional agencies such as RITA or CCA.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>School district income tax basics</h3>
              <p>
                Some Ohio school districts levy an additional income tax on
                residents. There are two main types:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Traditional base:</strong> Tax is based on Ohio
                  taxable income from your state return (wages, interest,
                  dividends, etc.).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Earned income base:</strong> Tax applies only to
                  earned income such as wages and self-employment income.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This calculator approximates both using your wage input. For a
                precise school district tax calculation, use your full Ohio
                taxable income and the official forms or software.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and important disclaimers</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This tool <strong>does not</strong> file your Ohio local tax
                  return.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Rates in the dropdowns are
                  <strong>illustrative only</strong> and may be outdated or
                  incomplete.
                </li>
                <li>
                  We do not model every local rule (loss carryforwards,
                  partial-year residency, non-wage income, etc.).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Always verify your actual rate and liability using:
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      Ohio Department of Taxation’s
                      <strong>The Finder</strong> (for municipal and school
                      district rates)
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Your city or village tax department (e.g., Columbus,
                      Toledo, Lima, Solon, Troy)
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Regional agencies such as <strong>RITA</strong> or
                      <strong>CCA</strong>
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions about Ohio local income tax</h2>

              <h3>Is Ohio local income tax deductible?</h3>
              <p>
                For federal tax purposes, local income taxes may be deductible
                as part of the state and local tax (SALT) deduction if you
                itemize, subject to the overall SALT cap. For Ohio state tax,
                municipal and school district income taxes are generally not
                deductible from Ohio taxable income. Check current IRS and Ohio
                rules or consult a tax professional.
              </p>

              <h3>What if I live in one Ohio city and work in another?</h3>
              <p>
                Often your employer withholds tax for the work city, and your
                home city may give you a partial or full credit for that tax.
                However, the rules and credit limits vary by municipality. Use
                the credit section of this calculator to approximate your net
                home city liability, then confirm with your city’s tax office.
              </p>

              <h3>Where can I find my school district income tax rate?</h3>
              <p>
                You can look up your school district and its tax rate using the
                Ohio Department of Taxation’s “The Finder” tool. Your voter
                registration card or property tax bill may also list your school
                district. Your pay stub may show school district withholding if
                your employer is withholding it.
              </p>

              <h3>Does this calculator handle non-wage income?</h3>
              <p>
                No. For simplicity, this tool uses your wage input as the tax
                base. Traditional school district income tax and some municipal
                taxes can apply to other types of income. For a complete
                calculation, use Ohio’s official forms, tax preparation
                software, or professional advice.
              </p>
